    <h2 class="font-bold text-center text-xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl text-violet-400 mt-32 mb-8">Mobility, Flexibility, & Body Structure</h2>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">Mobility disabilities affect a persons ability to move independently. People who have a mobility disability have trouble moving parts of their body and can have trouble walking without an assistive device. This type of disability can be present from birth, due to aging, or result of a disease. Mobility disabilities can be temporary, permanent, or recur. According to the CDC, 11% of adults in the US have mobility disability of some kind.</p>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">A person with mobility disabilities may have difficulty with fine motor control. For example, tieing shoes, using a mouse can be difficult for someone with hand tremors. Assistive technologies help people with mobility, for example vertical keyboards with a mouth stick, one-handed keyboards, expanded keyboards with raised sections and speech recognition software.</p>


